            <h3>What is a Security Logic?</h3>
            <div class="flexWrap">
            <div class="inlined left">     
                <p class="info">
           Security Logics provide the foundational assumptions upon which theories and views of security are based.
                </p>
                <p class="info">
The components of a Security Logic include:
                </p>
                <ol>
    <li>A particular understanding of the object/s, sites or ‘referent/s’ to be secured.
    </li>
    <li>An understanding of the relationship of these object/s or sites to a system, territory or collectivity containing the object/s or sites.
    </li>
    <li>A political attitude towards the securing of the system or collectivity, and towards those things and actors that lie outside this system.
    </li>
    <li>An understanding of the relationship the object/s or sites have to a technology (in the broadest sense of this word) or other form of agency that is capable of securing the object/s or sites.
    </li>
    <li>A Security Logic is constituted through and by a discourse that expresses the application of the logic to the object/s or sites. The discourse may be particular to that logic, or may feed into a combination of different logics.
    </li>
    <li>The discourse particular to the Security Logic creates A). a space of possibilities for the type of policies that can be conceived and enacted as part of the logic and B). creates a space of possible breakdown for that logic, areas in which the logic cannot be applied successfully.
    </li>
    <li>The Security Logic demonstrates a particular stance towards some or all other security logics. This stance concerns the degree of its own miscibility and permeability with respect to these other logics. (This operates on a scale from miscible to non-miscible, permeable to non-permeable).
    </li>
                </ol>
               <p class="info">
               Examples of Security Logics
                </p>
               <p class="info">
State or National Security Logic (negative/universalist, internally oriented rather than internationally oriented) - includes military and economic security logics.
                </p>
               <p class="info">
Societal Security Logic (negative and largely universalist) - includes the economic.
                </p>
               <p class="info">
Human Security Logic (positive). Identity politics security logic (positive) - individual rights security logic (positive).
                </p>
               <p class="info">
Planetary Security Logic (positive).
               </p>
               <p class="info">
               <span>Sources:</span> Barry Buzan, Lene Hansen, The Evolution of International Security Studies, Cambridge University Press, 2009. Roxanne Lynn Doty, Immigration and the politics of security, Security Studies, 8:2-3, 71-93, 1998. Rens van Munster, Logics of Security: The Copenhagen School, Risk Management and the War on Terror, University of Southern Denmark, 2005. 
                </p> 
