            <h3>Glossary</h3>
            <div class="left">
            <p class="info">
            <span>Securitisation</span>: ‘issues become security issues by virtue of a process of social construction, that is, securitization’ (Doty, 1998); the process of an issue (e.g. immigration, the environment etc.) becoming understood as a security issue.
            </p>
            <p class="info">
            <span>Negative Security:</span> ‘relates to the treatment of security as a concept we wish to avoid, one that should be invoked as little as possible. We value it negatively, or it is understood to represent a negative value’ (GjØrv, 2012) . ‘Can be understood as ‘security from’ (a threat)’ (Ibid.).
            </p>
            <p class="info">
            <span>Positive Security:</span> security perceived as ‘something that is positively valued, or as something that is good or desired. It is a good which provides the foundation to allow us to pursue our needs and interests and enjoy a full life’ (GjØrv, 2012). Can be understood as “security to’ or enabling’.
            </p>
            <p class="info">
            <span>Universalist Security:</span> The notion that there are universally applicable solutions for security issues.
            </p>
            <p class="info">
            <span>Real Politic:</span> Politics based on practical circumstances rather than moral or ideological values.  
            </p>
